I"&<h3 id="on-the-way-hungary-slovenia">On the Way: Hungary, Slovenia</h3>

<h4 id="balaton">Balaton</h4>
<p>Left the highway for two hours to have lunch at “Kistücsök” in a village on the lake shore.
Boring <em>catfish stew on pancakes</em> followed by adventurous <em>goulash soup</em> and <em>venison</em>.</p>

<!--more-->

<h3 id="veneto-and-emilia-romagna">Veneto and Emilia-Romagna</h3>

<h4 id="padua">Padua</h4>

<p>One should definitely visit the Scrovegni Chapel if in Padua
but this has to be planned in advance. In this case <em>mint coffee</em> and <em>zabaione</em>
at <a href="https://www.caffepedrocchi.it/en/"> Caffe Pedrocchi </a> (a local institution) 
is much more than a consolation prize.</p>

<h4 id="bologna">Bologna</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Tagliatelle al Ragu: Of course, we couldn’t pass through Bologna, known for its culinary heritage, without indulging in the iconic tagliatelle al ragu (what everyone else calls bolognese sauce). It’s like a warm hug from an Italian nonna.</li>
  <li>Leaning Towers: As we strolled through the city, we couldn’t help but notice Bologna’s leaning towers, one of them apparently even more inclined than the famous Pisa Tower. It seemed like Bologna was trying to out-lean Pisa in a friendly rivalry of tilting towers.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="tuscany">Tuscany</h3>

<h4 id="florence">Florence</h4>

<ul>
  <li>Bistecca alla fiorentina: As we arrived in Florence, the birthplace of the Renaissance, we couldn’t resist the temptation of a succulent Bistecca alla fiorentina. It felt like a masterpiece for our palates, cooked to perfection, and seasoned with history.</li>
  <li>Sandwich with Olives, Provolone, and Prosciutto on Schiacciata: For a quick, yet delightful bite, we relished a sandwich filled with olives, provolone, and prosciutto between slices of schiacciata. It was like a Tuscan landscape painted with flavors.</li>
</ul>

